e growth, cache footprint, and inter-service bandwidth before deep diving.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/foundations/lesson/performance-vs-scalability"><strong>Performance vs. scalability</strong> <small>Performance describes how fast one request path is now; scalability describes how gracefully the system behaves as load, data, or team size grows.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/foundations/lesson/latency-throughput-slos"><strong>Latency, throughput, and SLOs</strong> <small>Reason about how much work the system can do, how long each request takes, and which percentile targets users actually feel.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/foundations/lesson/availability-consistency-cap"><strong>Availability, consistency, and CAP trade-offs</strong> <small>Designs under partition must choose whether to prioritize fresh coordinated answers or continued service with potentially stale data.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/edge-and-routing"><strong>Networking, edge, and request routing</strong> <small>Learn how requests find your system, how traffic is distributed, and where you terminate policy, caching, and security controls.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/edge-and-routing/lesson/dns"><strong>DNS fundamentals</strong> <small>DNS maps names to endpoints and lets you steer traffic geographically, by health, or by weighted rollout without changing clients.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/edge-and-routing/lesson/cdn"><strong>Content delivery networks</strong> <small>A CDN moves cacheable content closer to users and can absorb large amounts of read traffic before requests ever reach origin infrastructure.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/edge-and-routing/lesson/load-balancing"><strong>Load balancing</strong> <small>Load balancers distribute requests across healthy backends and are the main control point for availability, failover, and safe scaling at the service edge.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/edge-and-routing/lesson/reverse-proxies-and-gateways"><strong>Reverse proxies, gateways, and edge policy</strong> <small>Reverse proxies shape inbound traffic by terminating TLS, applying caching and compression, enforcing auth, and routing to internal services.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/edge-and-routing/lesson/rate-limiting-and-edge-protection"><strong>Rate limiting and edge protection</strong> <small>Protect critical services from abusive clients, noisy neighbors, and self-inflicted overload before the core system becomes unstable.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/application-architecture"><strong>Application architecture and APIs</strong> <small>Choose service boundaries, communication styles, and coordination patterns that fit both the workload and the team operating the system.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/application-architecture/lesson/application-layer"><strong>Application layer responsibilities</strong> <small>The application layer turns requests into business actions, coordinates data access, and owns the product semantics that infrastructure alone cannot express.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/application-architecture/lesson/monolith-vs-microservices"><strong>Monoliths vs. microservices</strong> <small>Choose decomposition based on coordination cost, deployment independence, and team boundaries rather than trend pressure.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/application-architecture/lesson/service-discovery"><strong>Service discovery and coordination</strong> <small>Distributed services need a way to locate healthy instances, coordinate leaders, and react to topology changes without manual reconfiguration.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/application-architecture/lesson/api-design"><strong>API design: REST, RPC, and contracts</strong> <small>Pick communication styles that match workflow complexity, evolution needs, and performance sensitivity.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/application-architecture/lesson/realtime-delivery"><strong>Real-time delivery: WebSockets, SSE, and long polling</strong> <small>When users expect live updates, choose a delivery model that matches fan-out shape, connection count, and the direction of data flow.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/data-storage"><strong>Data storage and indexing</strong> <small>Match storage engines and data models to access patterns, write volume, consistency needs, and query flexibility.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/data-storage/lesson/relational-data-modeling"><strong>Relational data modeling and indexing</strong> <small>Relational databases remain the default for strongly constrained data, multi-row invariants, and flexible querying with mature operational tooling.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/data-storage/lesson/replication-and-failover"><strong>Replication and failover</strong> <small>Replicas improve read scale, durability, and recovery options, but they introduce lag, failover complexity, and write ownership decisions.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/data-storage/lesson/partitioning-and-sharding"><strong>Partitioning, federation, and sharding</strong> <small>Break data into smaller pieces when a single machine or logical schema becomes the bottleneck for size, throughput, or ownership.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/data-storage/lesson/nosql-landscape"><strong>The NoSQL landscape</strong> <small>NoSQL systems trade some relational flexibility for scale, availability patterns, schema freedom, or specialized query models.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/data-storage/lesson/storage-selection"><strong>Choosing the right storage mix</strong> <small>Most serious systems use more than one storage technology. The skill is choosing a small set whose strengths align with the workload and team.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/performance-and-resilience"><strong>Caching, asynchrony, and resilience</strong> <small>Reduce latency, smooth bursts, and survive failures by placing the right work in caches, queues, and resilient control loops.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/caching-layers"><strong>Caching layers and cache placement</strong> <small>Caching can remove repeated work from the critical path, but only if you choose the right layer and understand freshness requirements.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/cache-invalidation"><strong>Cache invalidation and update patterns</strong> <small>Pick an update pattern that matches read/write mix, freshness requirements, and operational simplicity.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/queues-and-streams"><strong>Queues, streams, and background work</strong> <small>Move non-interactive or bursty work off the request path so user-facing latency stays bounded and the system can absorb spikes gracefully.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/idempotency-retries-backpressure"><strong>Idempotency, retries, and back pressure</strong> <small>Make distributed workflows safe under duplicate delivery, partial failure, and overload instead of assuming every call succeeds exactly once.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/observability"><strong>Observability and operational feedback loops</strong> <small>Metrics, logs, traces, and alerting turn architecture choices into something operators can actually trust and improve.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/security-and-operations"><strong>Security, multi-region, and operations</strong> <small>Design systems that are safe to expose, recoverable during disasters, and maintainable by real teams over time.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 4 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/security-and-operations/lesson/security-basics"><strong>Security foundations for system design</strong> <small>Security choices should appear throughout the design, not as a last-minute box labeled auth.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/security-and-operations/lesson/multi-region-disaster-recovery"><strong>Multi-region design and disaster recovery</strong> <small>Use multiple regions when the business case justifies lower outage risk, lower latency, or data residency needs, while accepting the added coordination cost.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/security-and-operations/lesson/fault-tolerance-and-graceful-degradation"><strong>Fault tolerance and graceful degradation</strong> <small>Healthy systems keep the core user journey alive when dependencies fail by shedding optional work and falling back to simpler behavior.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/security-and-operations/lesson/deployment-capacity-cost"><strong>Deployments, capacity, and cost awareness</strong> <small>Production systems need safe release mechanics, realistic capacity headroom, and an explicit understanding of what the architecture costs to run.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/distributed-systems"><strong>Distributed systems building blocks</strong> <small>Go deeper on coordination, partitioning, probabilistic techniques, and workflow patterns that appear repeatedly in the primer and in senior-level interviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/distributed-systems/lesson/consistent-hashing-and-hot-keys"><strong>Consistent hashing and hot-key management</strong> <small>Partitioning strategy determines whether scale-out stays smooth or turns into painful rebalancing and overloaded shards.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/distributed-systems/lesson/consensus-quorums-and-leader-election"><strong>Consensus, quorums, and leader election</strong> <small>Some systems need a clear write owner or coordinated control plane, and that requires more than just adding replicas.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/distributed-systems/lesson/distributed-transactions-and-sagas"><strong>Distributed transactions, sagas, and idempotent workflows</strong> <small>Once one user action touches multiple services, the real design problem becomes how to preserve intent when part of the workflow fails halfway through.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/distributed-systems/lesson/probabilistic-data-structures"><strong>Probabilistic data structures and cardinality estimation</strong> <small>Bloom filters, sketches, and approximate counters let large systems answer useful questions cheaply when exact answers would be too slow or too expensive.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/distributed-systems/lesson/batch-stream-and-mapreduce"><strong>Batch processing, stream processing, and MapReduce</strong> <small>Not every workload belongs on the synchronous request path; many large systems depend on layered data pipelines for indexing, analytics, backfills, and asynchronous enrichment.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/product-patterns"><strong>Common product design patterns</strong> <small>Practice recurring architectures that appear across many interview prompts and real-world products.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/product-patterns/lesson/feed-timeline"><strong>Feeds and timelines</strong> <small>Feeds combine ranking, fan-out, caching, and read-time assembly decisions under heavy skewed traffic.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/product-patterns/lesson/file-storage-cdn"><strong>File upload, processing, and distribution</strong> <small>Media-heavy products require a pipeline for uploads, validation, durable storage, transformation, and fast global delivery.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/product-patterns/lesson/search-autocomplete"><strong>Search and autocomplete</strong> <small>Search systems combine ingestion, indexing, ranking, caching, and query-time latency controls.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/product-patterns/lesson/chat-notifications"><strong>Chat, presence, and notifications</strong> <small>Messaging products blend low-latency delivery, persistent history, fan-out, device state, and notification fallbacks.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/product-patterns/lesson/payments-ledger"><strong>Payments and ledger-style systems</strong> <small>Money movement demands idempotency, auditability, reconciliation, and a conservative approach to asynchronous side effects.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="./module/case-studies"><strong>Case studies and interview drills</strong> <small>Apply the concepts to end-to-end systems that commonly appear in interviews and architecture reviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="./module/case-studies/lesson/url-shortener"><strong>Case study: URL shortener</strong> <small>Design a service that creates short codes, resolves them quickly, tracks analytics, and avoids hot-key failures.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/case-studies/lesson/web-crawler"><strong>Case study: distributed web crawler</strong> <small>Crawlers combine frontier management, politeness, deduplication, storage, and ranking across many workers.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/case-studies/lesson/social-graph"><strong>Case study: social graph service</strong> <small>A social graph stores user relationships, supports high-volume fan-out queries, and powers many downstream ranking and recommendation systems.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/case-studies/lesson/query-cache"><strong>Case study: query-result cache</strong> <small>Design a cache that stores expensive query results while handling invalidation, skew, and freshness guarantees.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="./module/case-studies/lesson/scaling-playbook"><strong>Case study: scaling playbook</strong> <small>Practice describing how a simple single-region web application evolves through caching, queueing, partitioning, and global distribution over multiple growth stages.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><!--]--><!--]--></aside> <main class="page"><!--[--><!--[--><section class="hero panel"><div class="hero-grid"><div class="hero-card"><p class="eyebrow">Complete curriculum</p> <h1 class="hero-title">Study system design in the order interviews actually reward.</h1> <p class="hero-subtitle">Study foundations, distributed systems building blocks, architecture patterns, storage, caching, reliability, security, and end-to-end design drills in a mobile-friendly SvelteKit site with locally saved practice answers.</p> <div class="action-row"><a class="action-link primary" href="./module/foundations">Start with Foundations and estimation</a> <a class="action-link" href="./module/case-studies">Jump to case studies</a></div> <div class="action-row"><span class="pill">0 / 44 lessons complete</span> <span class="pill">Interactive practice labs with saved drafts</span> <span class="pill">Static build ready for Pages</span></div></div> <div class="hero-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study loop</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Start from user-visible requirements and failure expectations.</li><li>Quantify the read path, write path, and growth curve before choosing tools.</li><li>Use diagrams to explain where latency, state, and replication live.</li><li>Practice trade-offs, bottlenecks, and rollback plans out loud.</li><!--]--></ul></div></div></section> <section class="track-grid"><!--[--><article class="module-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interview sprint</p> <p>Use the lesson checklists and case studies to rehearse the order of an interview answer in 7 to 10 days.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Clarify requirements</li><li>Estimate scale</li><li>Draw the critical path</li><li>Deep dive into one risky area</li><li>Close with trade-offs and operations</li><!--]--></ul></article><article class="module-card"><p class="eyebrow">Deep understanding</p> <p>Move module by module to build intuition for when each component is useful and what it costs operationally.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Read the lesson summary</li><li>Study the diagram</li><li>Review failure modes</li><li>Answer the interview prompts</li><li>Mark the lesson complete after you can explain it aloud</li><!--]--></ul></article><article class="module-card"><p class="eyebrow">System walkthrough practice</p> <p>Use the case-study module to simulate whiteboard conversations and connect multiple lessons together.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Pick a product prompt</li><li>State assumptions</li><li>Choose storage and edge patterns</li><li>Add scaling and resilience controls</li><li>Compare alternatives</li><!--]--></ul></article><article class="module-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interactive answer drafting</p> <p>Open the practice lab inside each lesson, save your answer locally, and move through prompts one step at a time like a mock interview.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Open a lesson practice lab</li><li>Write a draft for the active prompt</li><li>Save the answer locally</li><li>Move to the next interview or design prompt</li><li>Return later and continue from your saved notes</li><!--]--></ul></article><!--]--></section> <section class="panel hero-card"><div class="action-row" style="justify-content: space-between; align-items: end;"><div><p class="eyebrow">Curriculum map</p> <h2>Modules and lesson progress</h2></div> <button class="reset-link" type="button">Reset progress</button></div> <div class="module-grid"><!--[--><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/foundations"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Foundations and estimation</h3></div> <p>Build the habit of turning vague prompts into concrete requirements, scale assumptions, and explicit trade-offs.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Frame product requirements before picking components</li><li>Estimate traffic, storage, and throughput with quick math</li><li>Explain performance, scalability, consistency, and availability in interviewer-friendly language</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/edge-and-routing"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Networking, edge, and request routing</h3></div> <p>Learn how requests find your system, how traffic is distributed, and where you terminate policy, caching, and security controls.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Explain DNS, CDNs, and load balancers as separate layers</li><li>Choose between L4 and L7 routing based on needed controls</li><li>Use edge layers to reduce latency and shield origin services</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/application-architecture"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Application architecture and APIs</h3></div> <p>Choose service boundaries, communication styles, and coordination patterns that fit both the workload and the team operating the system.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Select application decomposition patterns intentionally</li><li>Understand service discovery, coordination, and API trade-offs</li><li>Handle synchronous and real-time communication without hiding costs</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/data-storage"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Data storage and indexing</h3></div> <p>Match storage engines and data models to access patterns, write volume, consistency needs, and query flexibility.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Explain relational and NoSQL trade-offs clearly</li><li>Choose replication, partitioning, and indexing strategies</li><li>Recognize when one workload needs multiple storage systems</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/performance-and-resilience"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Caching, asynchrony, and resilience</h3></div> <p>Reduce latency, smooth bursts, and survive failures by placing the right work in caches, queues, and resilient control loops.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Use cache layers and invalidation strategies responsibly</li><li>Choose asynchronous patterns to absorb bursty work</li><li>Design retries, idempotency, and back pressure without making incidents worse</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/security-and-operations"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Security, multi-region, and operations</h3></div> <p>Design systems that are safe to expose, recoverable during disasters, and maintainable by real teams over time.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Apply practical authentication, authorization, and data protection patterns</li><li>Reason about multi-region architecture and disaster recovery</li><li>Include deployment, capacity, and cost controls in designs</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">4 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/4 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/distributed-systems"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Distributed systems building blocks</h3></div> <p>Go deeper on coordination, partitioning, probabilistic techniques, and workflow patterns that appear repeatedly in the primer and in senior-level interviews.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Explain the building blocks behind partitioning, coordination, and large-scale data movement</li><li>Recognize when to use quorums, hashing, probabilistic structures, and sagas</li><li>Connect these lower-level concepts back to product-facing system designs</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/product-patterns"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Common product design patterns</h3></div> <p>Practice recurring architectures that appear across many interview prompts and real-world products.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Recognize reusable patterns behind common product families</li><li>Explain fan-out, indexing, storage, and notification decisions</li><li>Use these patterns as building blocks in case studies</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><article class="module-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="./module/case-studies"><div><p class="eyebrow">Module</p> <h3>Case studies and interview drills</h3></div> <p>Apply the concepts to end-to-end systems that commonly appear in interviews and architecture reviews.</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Practice moving from requirements to a full design quickly</li><li>Use diagrams and trade-off language from earlier modules</li><li>Build confidence discussing bottlenecks, scaling steps, and failure modes</li><!--]--></ul> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span></div></a></article><!--]--></div></section> <section class="panel hero-card footer"><p class="eyebrow">Sources and attribution</p> <p class="footer-copy">Selected diagrams and topic framing were adapted from The System Design Primer by Donne Martin. Selected diagrams originate from <a href="https://github.com/donnemartin/system-design-primer" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">The System Design Primer</a> and are licensed under <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">CC BY 4.0</a>.</p></section><!--]--><!--]--></main></div></div><!--]--><!--]--> <!--[-1--><!--]--><!--]-->
 			
