or rates and retry budgets</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><!--]--></div> <div class="content-grid"><!--[0--><article class="diagram-card"><p class="eyebrow">Reference diagram</p> <h3>Visual anchor</h3> <img src="../../../../primer-images/bWxPtQA.png" alt="Distributed web crawler diagram" loading="lazy"/> <p>Crawlers highlight scheduling, politeness, deduplication, and pipeline resilience.</p> <p class="footer-copy">Adapted from The System Design Primer by Donne Martin (CC BY 4.0).</p></article><!--]--> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Checklist</p> <h3>Things to say clearly</h3> <ul class="checklist"><!--[--><li>Design a durable frontier and dedup pipeline.</li><li>Respect politeness and robots constraints.</li><li>Separate fetch, parse, and index stages.</li><li>Observe backlog, duplicate rate, and host-level failures.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Common pitfalls</p> <h3>What to avoid</h3> <ul class="pitfalls"><!--[--><li>Using one shared queue without host-level fairness.</li><li>Ignoring robots.txt or crawl budget semantics.</li><li>Treating parsing as synchronous with fetch.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interview prompts</p> <h3>Practice aloud</h3> <ul class="prompts"><!--[--><li>How would you avoid overwhelming a small website?</li><li>What data needs to be durable versus ephemeral?</li><li>How do you deduplicate pages efficiently?</li><!--]--></ul></article></div></section> <section class="panel hero-card practice-workspace"><div class="action-row" style="justify-content: space-between; align-items: end;"><div><p class="eyebrow">Interactive practice lab</p> <h2>Write, save, and move through the mock interview</h2> <p class="practice-copy">Answers stay in your browser so you can come back later without needing automated grading.</p></div> <div class="practice-status-group"><span class="pill">0/3 prompts saved</span> <span class="pill">Prompt 1 of 3</span></div></div> <div class="practice-layout"><article class="list-card practice-outline"><p class="eyebrow">Prompt flow</p> <h3>What you will practice</h3> <ol class="practice-step-list"><!--[--><li class="active"><div><strong>Interview opening</strong> <p>Frame the problem, scope, assumptions, and success metrics before you draw components.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><li><div><strong>Core architecture pass</strong> <p>Walk the critical path and write down the main components, data flow, and scale decisions.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><li><div><strong>Trade-offs and failure review</strong> <p>Close the answer the way a strong interview candidate would: trade-offs, failure modes, and operational follow-through.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><!--]--></ol></article> <article class="content-card practice-card"><div class="practice-card-header"><div><p class="eyebrow">design</p> <h3>Interview opening</h3></div> <span class="pill">Not saved yet</span></div> <p>You are starting a mock interview for "Case study: distributed web crawler". Capture the product assumptions, scale estimates, core APIs, and the first diagram you would draw.</p> <div class="practice-guidance"><p class="eyebrow">Use these guardrails</p> <ul><!--[--><li>How would you avoid overwhelming a small website?</li><li>Frontier and scheduling</li><li>Fetch and parse pipeline</li><li>Design a durable frontier and dedup pipeline.</li><!--]--></ul></div> <label class="practice-editor"><span class="eyebrow">Your answer</span> <textarea rows="12" placeholder="Write your notes, bullets, or interview answer here. Save before moving to the next prompt."></textarea></label> <div class="action-row"><button class="lesson-toggle" type="button" disabled="">Save answer</button> <button class="reset-link" type="button">Clear this lesson's saved answers</button></div> <div class="action-row practice-nav"><button class="action-link" type="button"