+    <div style="display: contents"><!--[--><!--[0--><!--[--><button aria-label="Close navigation" class="backdrop" type="button"></button> <div class="shell"><header class="topbar"><button class="nav-toggle" type="button">Browse topics</button> <div class="brand"><strong>System Design Copilot</strong> <span>0 / 44 lessons complete</span></div></header> <div class="layout"><aside class="sidebar"><section class="sidebar-header panel sidebar-card"><div><p class="eyebrow">System design prep</p> <h2>System Design Copilot</h2></div> <p class="muted">A deeper system design interview prep curriculum with topic guides, building blocks, trade-offs, case studies, and interactive practice labs.</p> <a class="action-link primary" href="../../../../">Open curriculum home</a></section> <section class="panel sidebar-card sidebar-search"><label><span class="eyebrow">Search lessons</span> <input value="" type="search" placeholder="Search modules and topics"/></label></section> <section class="panel sidebar-card sidebar-stats"><article class="stat"><span class="eyebrow">Modules</span> <strong>9</strong></article> <article class="stat"><span class="eyebrow">Progress</span> <strong>0/44</strong></article></section> <!--[0--><!--[--><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations"><strong>Foundations and estimation</strong> <small>Build the habit of turning vague prompts into concrete requirements, scale assumptions, and explicit trade-offs.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/problem-framing"><strong>Problem framing and requirements</strong> <small>Start every design with the user journey, hard constraints, and the two or three metrics that will define success.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/capacity-estimation"><strong>Back-of-the-envelope estimation</strong> <small>Use quick arithmetic to size read/write traffic, storage growth, cache footprint, and inter-service bandwidth before deep diving.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/performance-vs-scalability"><strong>Performance vs. scalability</strong> <small>Performance describes how fast one request path is now; scalability describes how gracefully the system behaves as load, data, or team size grows.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/latency-throughput-slos"><strong>Latency, throughput, and SLOs</strong> <small>Reason about how much work the system can do, how long each request takes, and which percentile targets users actually feel.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/availability-consistency-cap"><strong>Availability, consistency, and CAP trade-offs</strong> <small>Designs under partition must choose whether to prioritize fresh coordinated answers or continued service with potentially stale data.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing"><strong>Networking, edge, and request routing</strong> <small>Learn how requests find your system, how traffic is distributed, and where you terminate policy, caching, and security controls.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/dns"><strong>DNS fundamentals</strong> <small>DNS maps names to endpoints and lets you steer traffic geographically, by health, or by weighted rollout without changing clients.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/cdn"><strong>Content delivery networks</strong> <small>A CDN moves cacheable content closer to users and can absorb large amounts of read traffic before requests ever reach origin infrastructure.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/load-balancing"><strong>Load balancing</strong> <small>Load balancers distribute requests across healthy backends and are the main control point for availability, failover, and safe scaling at the service edge.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/reverse-proxies-and-gateways"><strong>Reverse proxies, gateways, and edge policy</strong> <small>Reverse proxies shape inbound traffic by terminating TLS, applying caching and compression, enforcing auth, and routing to internal services.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/rate-limiting-and-edge-protection"><strong>Rate limiting and edge protection</strong> <small>Protect critical services from abusive clients, noisy neighbors, and self-inflicted overload before the core system becomes unstable.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture"><strong>Application architecture and APIs</strong> <small>Choose service boundaries, communication styles, and coordination patterns that fit both the workload and the team operating the system.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/application-layer"><strong>Application layer responsibilities</strong> <small>The application layer turns requests into business actions, coordinates data access, and owns the product semantics that infrastructure alone cannot express.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/monolith-vs-microservices"><strong>Monoliths vs. microservices</strong> <small>Choose decomposition based on coordination cost, deployment independence, and team boundaries rather than trend pressure.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/service-discovery"><strong>Service discovery and coordination</strong> <small>Distributed services need a way to locate healthy instances, coordinate leaders, and react to topology changes without manual reconfiguration.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/api-design"><strong>API design: REST, RPC, and contracts</strong> <small>Pick communication styles that match workflow complexity, evolution needs, and performance sensitivity.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/realtime-delivery"><strong>Real-time delivery: WebSockets, SSE, and long polling</strong> <small>When users expect live updates, choose a delivery model that matches fan-out shape, connection count, and the direction of data flow.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage"><strong>Data storage and indexing</strong> <small>Match storage engines and data models to access patterns, write volume, consistency needs, and query flexibility.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/relational-data-modeling"><strong>Relational data modeling and indexing</strong> <small>Relational databases remain the default for strongly constrained data, multi-row invariants, and flexible querying with mature operational tooling.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/replication-and-failover"><strong>Replication and failover</strong> <small>Replicas improve read scale, durability, and recovery options, but they introduce lag, failover complexity, and write ownership decisions.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/partitioning-and-sharding"><strong>Partitioning, federation, and sharding</strong> <small>Break data into smaller pieces when a single machine or logical schema becomes the bottleneck for size, throughput, or ownership.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/nosql-landscape"><strong>The NoSQL landscape</strong> <small>NoSQL systems trade some relational flexibility for scale, availability patterns, schema freedom, or specialized query models.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/storage-selection"><strong>Choosing the right storage mix</strong> <small>Most serious systems use more than one storage technology. The skill is choosing a small set whose strengths align with the workload and team.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience"><strong>Caching, asynchrony, and resilience</strong> <small>Reduce latency, smooth bursts, and survive failures by placing the right work in caches, queues, and resilient control loops.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/caching-layers"><strong>Caching layers and cache placement</strong> <small>Caching can remove repeated work from the critical path, but only if you choose the right layer and understand freshness requirements.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/cache-invalidation"><strong>Cache invalidation and update patterns</strong> <small>Pick an update pattern that matches read/write mix, freshness requirements, and operational simplicity.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/queues-and-streams"><strong>Queues, streams, and background work</strong> <small>Move non-interactive or bursty work off the request path so user-facing latency stays bounded and the system can absorb spikes gracefully.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/idempotency-retries-backpressure"><strong>Idempotency, retries, and back pressure</strong> <small>Make distributed workflows safe under duplicate delivery, partial failure, and overload instead of assuming every call succeeds exactly once.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/observability"><strong>Observability and operational feedback loops</strong> <small>Metrics, logs, traces, and alerting turn architecture choices into something operators can actually trust and improve.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations"><strong>Security, multi-region, and operations</strong> <small>Design systems that are safe to expose, recoverable during disasters, and maintainable by real teams over time.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 4 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/security-basics"><strong>Security foundations for system design</strong> <small>Security choices should appear throughout the design, not as a last-minute box labeled auth.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/multi-region-disaster-recovery"><strong>Multi-region design and disaster recovery</strong> <small>Use multiple regions when the business case justifies lower outage risk, lower latency, or data residency needs, while accepting the added coordination cost.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/fault-tolerance-and-graceful-degradation"><strong>Fault tolerance and graceful degradation</strong> <small>Healthy systems keep the core user journey alive when dependencies fail by shedding optional work and falling back to simpler behavior.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/deployment-capacity-cost"><strong>Deployments, capacity, and cost awareness</strong> <small>Production systems need safe release mechanics, realistic capacity headroom, and an explicit understanding of what the architecture costs to run.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems"><strong>Distributed systems building blocks</strong> <small>Go deeper on coordination, partitioning, probabilistic techniques, and workflow patterns that appear repeatedly in the primer and in senior-level interviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/consistent-hashing-and-hot-keys"><strong>Consistent hashing and hot-key management</strong> <small>Partitioning strategy determines whether scale-out stays smooth or turns into painful rebalancing and overloaded shards.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/consensus-quorums-and-leader-election"><strong>Consensus, quorums, and leader election</strong> <small>Some systems need a clear write owner or coordinated control plane, and that requires more than just adding replicas.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/distributed-transactions-and-sagas"><strong>Distributed transactions, sagas, and idempotent workflows</strong> <small>Once one user action touches multiple services, the real design problem becomes how to preserve intent when part of the workflow fails halfway through.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/probabilistic-data-structures"><strong>Probabilistic data structures and cardinality estimation</strong> <small>Bloom filters, sketches, and approximate counters let large systems answer useful questions cheaply when exact answers would be too slow or too expensive.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/batch-stream-and-mapreduce"><strong>Batch processing, stream processing, and MapReduce</strong> <small>Not every workload belongs on the synchronous request path; many large systems depend on layered data pipelines for indexing, analytics, backfills, and asynchronous enrichment.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns"><strong>Common product design patterns</strong> <small>Practice recurring architectures that appear across many interview prompts and real-world products.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/feed-timeline"><strong>Feeds and timelines</strong> <small>Feeds combine ranking, fan-out, caching, and read-time assembly decisions under heavy skewed traffic.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/file-storage-cdn"><strong>File upload, processing, and distribution</strong> <small>Media-heavy products require a pipeline for uploads, validation, durable storage, transformation, and fast global delivery.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/search-autocomplete"><strong>Search and autocomplete</strong> <small>Search systems combine ingestion, indexing, ranking, caching, and query-time latency controls.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/chat-notifications"><strong>Chat, presence, and notifications</strong> <small>Messaging products blend low-latency delivery, persistent history, fan-out, device state, and notification fallbacks.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/payments-ledger"><strong>Payments and ledger-style systems</strong> <small>Money movement demands idempotency, auditability, reconciliation, and a conservative approach to asynchronous side effects.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies"><strong>Case studies and interview drills</strong> <small>Apply the concepts to end-to-end systems that commonly appear in interviews and architecture reviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/url-shortener"><strong>Case study: URL shortener</strong> <small>Design a service that creates short codes, resolves them quickly, tracks analytics, and avoids hot-key failures.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/web-crawler"><strong>Case study: distributed web crawler</strong> <small>Crawlers combine frontier management, politeness, deduplication, storage, and ranking across many workers.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/social-graph"><strong>Case study: social graph service</strong> <small>A social graph stores user relationships, supports high-volume fan-out queries, and powers many downstream ranking and recommendation systems.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/query-cache"><strong>Case study: query-result cache</strong> <small>Design a cache that stores expensive query results while handling invalidation, skew, and freshness guarantees.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/scaling-playbook"><strong>Case study: scaling playbook</strong> <small>Practice describing how a simple single-region web application evolves through caching, queueing, partitioning, and global distribution over multiple growth stages.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><!--]--><!--]--></aside> <main class="page"><!--[--><!--[--><section class="panel hero-card"><div class="breadcrumb"><a href="../../../../">Curriculum</a> <span>→</span> <a href="../../../../module/distributed-systems">Distributed systems building blocks</a> <span>→</span> <span>Consistent hashing and hot-key management</span></div> <p class="eyebrow">Lesson 1 of 5</p> <h1>Consistent hashing and hot-key management</h1> <p class="hero-subtitle">Partitioning strategy determines whether scale-out stays smooth or turns into painful rebalancing and overloaded shards.</p> <div class="action-row"><span class="pill">30-40 min</span> <span class="pill">Distributed systems building blocks</span> <button class="lesson-toggle" type="button">Mark complete</button></div></section> <section class="section-grid"><div class="content-grid"><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Why it matters</p> <h3>Interview framing</h3> <p>Many system design answers mention sharding, but stronger candidates can explain how data moves during capacity changes and how to survive skewed traffic.</p></article> <!--[--><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Why consistent hashing exists</h3> <p>Naive modulo-based sharding reshuffles a large fraction of keys whenever the node count changes. Consistent hashing reduces reshuffling so scale events and failures are less disruptive.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Map both nodes and keys onto a logical ring or token space</li><li>Only a bounded slice of keys moves when capacity changes</li><li>Virtual nodes smooth uneven hardware and failure domains</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Hot partitions still need extra controls</h3> <p>Even a good partitioning strategy can collapse under celebrity users, trending objects, or tenant imbalance. Plan for skew rather than assuming uniform traffic.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Detect hot keys with per-partition saturation metrics</li><li>Use replication, selective fan-out, or request coalescing for extreme skew</li><li>Choose partition keys that follow the read and write path, not just the schema</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Tie hashing to operational behavior</h3> <p>Partitioning decisions affect rebalancing speed, cache locality, failure isolation, and incident recovery. Explain those effects, not only the algorithm.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Discuss how nodes join, leave, and recover</li><li>Separate logical ownership from physical placement</li><li>Mention metadata coordination and replica movement cost</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><!--]--></div> <div class="content-grid"><!--[-1--><!--]--> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Checklist</p> <h3>Things to say clearly</h3> <ul class="checklist"><!--[--><li>Explain why modulo sharding causes painful remaps.</li><li>Mention virtual nodes or tokens for balance.</li><li>Call out hot-key mitigation separately from normal partitioning.</li><li>Describe what happens during rebalance or node failure.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Common pitfalls</p> <h3>What to avoid</h3> <ul class="pitfalls"><!--[--><li>Assuming even key distribution in real workloads.</li><li>Treating partitioning as only a data-model decision.</li><li>Ignoring rebalancing bandwidth and cache churn.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interview prompts</p> <h3>Practice aloud</h3> <ul class="prompts"><!--[--><li>Why is consistent hashing often preferred over modulo-based partitioning?</li><li>How would you handle a celebrity account that overwhelms one shard?</li><li>What operational metrics tell you a partitioning strategy is breaking down?</li><!--]--></ul></article></div></section> <section class="panel hero-card practice-workspace"><div class="action-row" style="justify-content: space-between; align-items: end;"><div><p class="eyebrow">Interactive practice lab</p> <h2>Write, save, and move through the mock interview</h2> <p class="practice-copy">Answers stay in your browser so you can come back later without needing automated grading.</p></div> <div class="practice-status-group"><span class="pill">0/3 prompts saved</span> <span class="pill">Prompt 1 of 3</span></div></div> <div class="practice-layout"><article class="list-card practice-outline"><p class="eyebrow">Prompt flow</p> <h3>What you will practice</h3> <ol class="practice-step-list"><!--[--><li class="active"><div><strong>Explain the concept</strong> <p>Explain the topic in interviewer-friendly language before diving into implementation details.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><li><div><strong>System design drill</strong> <p>Walk the critical path and write down the main components, data flow, and scale decisions.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><li><div><strong>Trade-offs and failure review</strong> <p>Close the answer the way a strong interview candidate would: trade-offs, failure modes, and operational follow-through.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><!--]--></ol></article> <article class="content-card practice-card"><div class="practice-card-header"><div><p class="eyebrow">interview</p> <h3>Explain the concept</h3></div> <span class="pill">Not saved yet</span></div> <p>Teach "Consistent hashing and hot-key management" back to an interviewer. Summarize what it is, when you would use it, and why it matters in a real system.</p> <div class="practice-guidance"><p class="eyebrow">Use these guardrails</p> <ul><!--[--><li>Why is consistent hashing often preferred over modulo-based partitioning?</li><li>Why consistent hashing exists</li><li>Hot partitions still need extra controls</li><li>Explain why modulo sharding causes painful remaps.</li><!--]--></ul></div> <label class="practice-editor"><span class="eyebrow">Your answer</span> <textarea rows="12" placeholder="Write your notes, bullets, or interview answer here. Save before moving to the next prompt."></textarea></label> <div class="action-row"><button class="lesson-toggle" typ