></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/distributed-systems"><strong>Distributed systems building blocks</strong> <small>Go deeper on coordination, partitioning, probabilistic techniques, and workflow patterns that appear repeatedly in the primer and in senior-level interviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/consistent-hashing-and-hot-keys"><strong>Consistent hashing and hot-key management</strong> <small>Partitioning strategy determines whether scale-out stays smooth or turns into painful rebalancing and overloaded shards.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/consensus-quorums-and-leader-election"><strong>Consensus, quorums, and leader election</strong> <small>Some systems need a clear write owner or coordinated control plane, and that requires more than just adding replicas.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/distributed-transactions-and-sagas"><strong>Distributed transactions, sagas, and idempotent workflows</strong> <small>Once one user action touches multiple services, the real design problem becomes how to preserve intent when part of the workflow fails halfway through.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/probabilistic-data-structures"><strong>Probabilistic data structures and cardinality estimation</strong> <small>Bloom filters, sketches, and approximate counters let large systems answer useful questions cheaply when exact answers would be too slow or too expensive.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/batch-stream-and-mapreduce"><strong>Batch processing, stream processing, and MapReduce</strong> <small>Not every workload belongs on the synchronous request path; many large systems depend on layered data pipelines for indexing, analytics, backfills, and asynchronous enrichment.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/product-patterns"><strong>Common product design patterns</strong> <small>Practice recurring architectures that appear across many interview prompts and real-world products.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/product-patterns/lesson/feed-timeline"><strong>Feeds and timelines</strong> <small>Feeds combine ranking, fan-out, caching, and read-time assembly decisions under heavy skewed traffic.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/product-patterns/lesson/file-storage-cdn"><strong>File upload, processing, and distribution</strong> <small>Media-heavy products require a pipeline for uploads, validation, durable storage, transformation, and fast global delivery.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/product-patterns/lesson/search-autocomplete"><strong>Search and autocomplete</strong> <small>Search systems combine ingestion, indexing, ranking, caching, and query-time latency controls.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/product-patterns/lesson/chat-notifications"><strong>Chat, presence, and notifications</strong> <small>Messaging products blend low-latency delivery, persistent history, fan-out, device state, and notification fallbacks.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/product-patterns/lesson/payments-ledger"><strong>Payments and ledger-style systems</strong> <small>Money movement demands idempotency, auditability, reconciliation, and a conservative approach to asynchronous side effects.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/case-studies"><strong>Case studies and interview drills</strong> <small>Apply the concepts to end-to-end systems that commonly appear in interviews and architecture reviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/case-studies/lesson/url-shortener"><strong>Case study: URL shortener</strong> <small>Design a service that creates short codes, resolves them quickly, tracks analytics, and avoids hot-key failures.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/case-studies/lesson/web-crawler"><strong>Case study: distributed web crawler</strong> <small>Crawlers combine frontier management, politeness, deduplication, storage, and ranking across many workers.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/case-studies/lesson/social-graph"><strong>Case study: social graph service</strong> <small>A social graph stores user relationships, supports high-volume fan-out queries, and powers many downstream ranking and recommendation systems.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/case-studies/lesson/query-cache"><strong>Case study: query-result cache</strong> <small>Design a cache that stores expensive query results while handling invalidation, skew, and freshness guarantees.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/case-studies/lesson/scaling-playbook"><strong>Case study: scaling playbook</strong> <small>Practice describing how a simple single-region web application evolves through caching, queueing, partitioning, and global distribution over multiple growth stages.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><!--]--><!--]--></aside> <main class="page"><!--[--><!--[--><section class="panel hero-card"><div class="breadcrumb"><a href="../../">Curriculum</a> <span>→</span> <span>Networking, edge, and request routing</span></div> <p class="eyebrow">Module overview</p> <h1>Networking, edge, and request routing</h1> <p class="hero-subtitle">Learn how requests find your system, how traffic is distributed, and where you terminate policy, caching, and security controls.</p> <div class="action-row"><span class="pill">5 lessons</span> <span class="pill">0/5 complete</span> <a class="action-link primary" href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/dns">Start module</a></div></section> <section class="list-grid"><article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Objectives</p> <h3>What to master here</h3> <ul><!--[--><li>Explain DNS, CDNs, and load balancers as separate layers</li><li>Choose between L4 and L7 routing based on needed controls</li><li>Use edge layers to reduce latency and shield origin services</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">How to use this module</p> <h3>Practice flow</h3> <ul><li>Read the summary and explain the core trade-off in your own words.</li> <li>Study the diagram and identify the critical path or failure boundary.</li> <li>Answer the interview prompts aloud before marking the lesson complete.</li></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interview signal</p> <h3>What reviewers expect</h3> <ul><li>Clear assumptions and estimated scale.</li> <li>Justified component choices instead of pattern dumping.</li> <li>Awareness of operations, failure modes, and trade-offs.</li></ul></article></section> <section class="lesson-grid"><!--[--><article class="lesson-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/dns"><div><p class="eyebrow">Lesson 1</p> <h3>DNS fundamentals</h3></div> <p>DNS maps names to endpoints and lets you steer traffic geographically, by health, or by weighted rollout without changing clients.</p> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">25-35 min</span> <span class="progress-badge">Open</span></div></a></article><article class="lesson-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/cdn"><div><p class="eyebrow">Lesson 2</p> <h3>Content delivery networks</h3></div> <p>A CDN moves cacheable content closer to users and can absorb large amounts of read traffic before requests ever reach origin infrastructure.</p> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">25-35 min</span> <span class="progress-badge">Open</span></div></a></article><article class="lesson-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/load-balancing"><div><p class="eyebrow">Lesson 3</p> <h3>Load balancing</h3></div> <p>Load balancers distribute requests across healthy backends and are the main control point for availability, failover, and safe scaling at the service edge.</p> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">25-35 min</span> <span class="progress-badge">Open</span></div></a></article><article class="lesson-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/reverse-proxies-and-gateways"><div><p class="eyebrow">Lesson 4</p> <h3>Reverse proxies, gateways, and edge policy</h3></div> <p>Reverse proxies shape inbound traffic by terminating TLS, applying caching and compression, enforcing auth, and routing to internal services.</p> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">25-35 min</span> <span class="progress-badge">Open</span></div></a></article><article class="lesson-card"><a class="topic-card-link" href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/rate-limiting-and-edge-protection"><div><p class="eyebrow">Lesson 5</p> <h3>Rate limiting and edge protection</h3></div> <p>Protect critical services from abusive clients, noisy neighbors, and self-inflicted overload before the core system becomes unstable.</p> <div class="card-meta"><span class="pill">25-35 min</span> <span class="progress-badge">Open</span></div></a></article><!--]--></section><!--]--><!--]--></main></div></div><!--]--><!--]--> <!--[-1--><!--]--><!--]-->
 			
