strong> <small>Load balancers distribute requests across healthy backends and are the main control point for availability, failover, and safe scaling at the service edge.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/reverse-proxies-and-gateways"><strong>Reverse proxies, gateways, and edge policy</strong> <small>Reverse proxies shape inbound traffic by terminating TLS, applying caching and compression, enforcing auth, and routing to internal services.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/rate-limiting-and-edge-protection"><strong>Rate limiting and edge protection</strong> <small>Protect critical services from abusive clients, noisy neighbors, and self-inflicted overload before the core system becomes unstable.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/application-architecture"><strong>Application architecture and APIs</strong> <small>Choose service boundaries, communication styles, and coordination patterns that fit both the workload and the team operating the system.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/application-architecture/lesson/application-layer"><strong>Application layer responsibilities</strong> <small>The application layer turns requests into business actions, coordinates data access, and owns the product semantics that infrastructure alone cannot express.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/application-architecture/lesson/monolith-vs-microservices"><strong>Monoliths vs. microservices</strong> <small>Choose decomposition based on coordination cost, deployment independence, and team boundaries rather than trend pressure.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../module/application-architecture/lesson/service-discovery"><strong>Service discovery and coordination</strong> <small>Distributed services need a way to locate