ma becomes the bottleneck for size, throughput, or ownership.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/nosql-landscape"><strong>The NoSQL landscape</strong> <small>NoSQL systems trade some relational flexibility for scale, availability patterns, schema freedom, or specialized query models.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/storage-selection"><strong>Choosing the right storage mix</strong> <small>Most serious systems use more than one storage technology. The skill is choosing a small set whose strengths align with the workload and team.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience"><strong>Caching, asynchrony, and resilience</strong> <small>Reduce latency, smooth bursts, and survive failures by placing the right work in caches, queues, and resilient control loops.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/caching-layers"><strong>Caching layers and cache placement</strong> <small>Caching can remove repeated work from the critical path, but only if you choose the right layer and understand freshness requirements.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/cache-invalidation"><strong>Cache invalidation and update patterns</strong> <small>Pick an update pattern that matches read/write mix, freshness requirements, and operational simplicity.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/queues-and-streams"><strong>Queues, streams, and background work</strong> <small>Move non-interactive or bursty work off the request path so user-facing latency stays bounded and the system can absorb spikes gracefully.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/idempotency-retries-backpressure"><strong>Idempotency, retries, and back pressure</strong> <small>Make distributed workflows safe under duplicate delivery, partial failure, and overload instead of assuming every call succeeds exactly once.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/observability"><strong>Observability and operational feedback loops</strong> <small>Metrics, logs, traces, and alerting turn architecture choices into something operators can actually trust and improve.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations"><strong>Security, multi-region, and operations</strong> <small>Design systems that are safe to expose, recoverable during disasters, and maintainable by real teams over time.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 4 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/security-basics"><strong>Security foundations for system design</strong> <small>Security choices should appear throughout the design, not as a last-minute box labeled auth.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/multi-region-disaster-recovery"><strong>Multi-region design and disaster recovery</strong> <small>Use multiple regions when the business case justifies lower outage risk, lower latency, or data residency needs, while accepting the added coordination cost.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/fault-tolerance-and-graceful-degradation"><strong>Fault tolerance and graceful degradation</strong> <small>Healthy systems keep the core user journey alive when dependencies fail by shedding optional work and falling back to simpler behavior.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/deployment-capacity-cost"><strong>Deployments, capacity, and cost awareness</strong> <small>Production systems need safe release mechanics, realistic capacity headroom, and an explicit understanding of what the architecture costs to run.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems"><strong>Distributed systems building blocks</strong> <small>Go deeper on coordination, partitioning, probabilistic techniques, and workflow patterns that appear repeatedly in the primer and in senior-level interviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/consistent-hashing-and-hot-keys"><strong>Consistent hashing and hot-key management</strong> <small>Partitioning strategy determines whether scale-out stays smooth or turns into painful rebalancing and overloaded shards.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/consensus-quorums-and-leader-election"><strong>Consensus, quorums, and leader election</strong> <small>Some systems need a clear write owner or coordinated control plane, and that requires more than just adding replicas.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/distributed-transactions-and-sagas"><strong>Distributed transactions, sagas, and idempotent workflows</strong> <small>Once one user action touches multiple services, the real design problem becomes how to preserve intent when part of the workflow fails halfway through.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/probabilistic-data-structures"><strong>Probabilistic data structures and cardinality estimation</strong> <small>Bloom filters, sketches, and approximate counters let large systems answer useful questions cheaply when exact answers would be too slow or too expensive.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/distributed-systems/lesson/batch-stream-and-mapreduce"><strong>Batch processing, stream processing, and MapReduce</strong> <small>Not every workload belongs on the synchronous request path; many large systems depend on layered data pipelines for indexing, analytics, backfills, and asynchronous enrichment.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns"><strong>Common product design patterns</strong> <small>Practice recurring architectures that appear across many interview prompts and real-world products.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/feed-timeline"><strong>Feeds and timelines</strong> <small>Feeds combine ranking, fan-out, caching, and read-time assembly decisions under heavy skewed traffic.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/file-storage-cdn"><strong>File upload, processing, and distribution</strong> <small>Media-heavy products require a pipeline for uploads, validation, durable storage, transformation, and fast global delivery.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/search-autocomplete"><strong>Search and autocomplete</strong> <small>Search systems combine ingestion, indexing, ranking, caching, and query-time latency controls.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/chat-notifications"><strong>Chat, presence, and notifications</strong> <small>Messaging products blend low-latency delivery, persistent history, fan-out, device state, and notification fallbacks.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/payments-ledger"><strong>Payments and ledger-style systems</strong> <small>Money movement demands idempotency, auditability, reconciliation, and a conservative approach to asynchronous side effects.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies"><strong>Case studies and interview drills</strong> <small>Apply the concepts to end-to-end systems that commonly appear in interviews and architecture reviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/url-shortener"><strong>Case study: URL shortener</strong> <small>Design a service that creates short codes, resolves them quickly, tracks analytics, and avoids hot-key failures.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/web-crawler"><strong>Case study: distributed web crawler</strong> <small>Crawlers combine frontier management, politeness, deduplication, storage, and ranking across many workers.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/social-graph"><strong>Case study: social graph service</strong> <small>A social graph stores user relationships, supports high-volume fan-out queries, and powers many downstream ranking and recommendation systems.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/query-cache"><strong>Case study: query-result cache</strong> <small>Design a cache that stores expensive query results while handling invalidation, skew, and freshness guarantees.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/scaling-playbook"><strong>Case study: scaling playbook</strong> <small>Practice describing how a simple single-region web application evolves through caching, queueing, partitioning, and global distribution over multiple growth stages.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><!--]--><!--]--></aside> <main class="page"><!--[--><!--[--><section class="panel hero-card"><div class="breadcrumb"><a href="../../../../">Curriculum</a> <span>→</span> <a href="../../../../module/product-patterns">Common product design patterns</a> <span>→</span> <span>Payments and ledger-style systems</span></div> <p class="eyebrow">Lesson 5 of 5</p> <h1>Payments and ledger-style systems</h1> <p class="hero-subtitle">Money movement demands idempotency, auditability, reconciliation, and a conservative approach to asynchronous side effects.</p> <div class="action-row"><span class="pill">25-35 min</span> <span class="pill">Common product design patterns</span> <button class="lesson-toggle" type="button">Mark complete</button></div></section> <section class="section-grid"><div class="content-grid"><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Why it matters</p> <h3>Interview framing</h3> <p>Even if you never design a payments product in production, this lesson forces precise thinking about correctness under failure.</p></article> <!--[--><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Double-entry and immutable events</h3> <p>Represent money movement as balanced ledger entries or state transitions so you can audit and reconcile every step.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Avoid destructive updates to balances without history</li><li>Use idempotency keys for external and internal requests</li><li>Separate authorization, capture, settlement, and refund states</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Synchronous correctness, asynchronous integrations</h3> <p>The core ledger path often requires strong correctness, while email, analytics, and some partner updates can be asynchronous.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Persist the canonical transaction result before side effects</li><li>Use outbox or event publication for downstream tasks</li><li>Plan reconciliation with payment processors or banks</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Operational safeguards</h3> <p>Retries, duplicate callbacks, partial outages, and compliance audits are normal, so design the workflow as a recoverable state machine.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Hold suspicious transactions for review when needed</li><li>Audit privileged operations and schema changes</li><li>Observe settlement lag, retry rates, and mismatch counts</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><!--]--></div> <div class="content-grid"><!--[-1--><!--]--> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Checklist</p> <h3>Things to say clearly</h3> <ul class="checklist"><!--[--><li>Use immutable ledger events or equivalent audit records.</li><li>Make transaction creation idempotent.</li><li>Keep the core money path strongly correct.</li><li>Plan reconciliation and dispute workflows.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Common pitfalls</p> <h3>What to avoid</h3> <ul class="pitfalls"><!--[--><li>Using write-behind caches for balances.</li><li>Letting downstream notifications define transaction truth.</li><li>Ignoring external callback duplication and delayed settlement.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interview prompts</p> <h3>Practice aloud</h3> <ul class="prompts"><!--[--><li>How would you design a wallet transfer API?</li><li>What happens if a partner callback is retried days later?</li><li>Why is an append-only ledger safer than just mutating balances?</li><!--]--></ul></article></div></section> <section class="panel hero-card practice-workspace"><div class="action-row" style="justify-content: space-between; align-items: end;"><div><p class="eyebrow">Interactive practice lab</p> <h2>Write, save, and move through the mock interview</h2> <p class="practice-copy">Answers stay in your browser so you can come back later without needing automated grading.</p></div> <div class="practice-status-group"><span class="pill">0/3 prompts saved</span> <span class="pill">Prompt 1 of 3</span></div></div> <div class="practice-layout"><article class="list-card practice-outline"><p class="eyebrow">Prompt flow</p> <h3>What you will practice</h3> <ol class="practice-step-list"><!--[--><li class="active"><div><strong>Explain the concept</strong> <p>Explain the topic in interviewer-friendly language before diving into implementation details.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><li><div><strong>System design drill</strong> <p>Walk the critical path and write down the main components, data flow, and scale decisions.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><li><div><strong>Trade-offs and failure review</strong> <p>Close the answer the way a strong interview candidate would: trade-offs, failure modes, and operational follow-through.</p></div> <span class="progress-badge">Draft</span></li><!--]--></ol></article> <article class="content-card practice-card"><div class="practice-card-header"><div><p class="eyebrow">interview</p> <h3>Explain the concept</h3></div> <span class="pill">Not saved yet</span></div> <p>Teach "Payments and ledger-style systems" back to an interviewer. Summarize what it is, when you would use it, and why it matters in a real system.</p> <div class="practice-guidance"><p class="eyebrow">Use these guardrails</p> <ul><!--[--><li>How would you design a wallet transfer API?</li><li>Double-entry and immutable events</li><li>Synchronous correctness, asynchronous integrations</li><li>Use immutable ledger events or equivalent audit records.</li><!--]--></ul></div> <label class="practice-editor"><span class="eyebrow">Your answer</span> <textarea rows="12" placeholder="Write your notes, bullets, or interview answer here. Save before moving to the next prompt."></textarea></label> <div class="action-row"><button class="lesson-toggle" type="button" disabled="">Save answer</button> <button class="reset-link" type="button">Clear this lesson's saved answers</button></div> <div class="action-row practice-nav"><button class="action-link" type="button" disabled="">← Previous prompt</button> <!--[0--><button class="action-link primary" type="bu