-    <div style="display: contents"><!--[--><!--[0--><!--[--><button aria-label="Close navigation" class="backdrop" type="button"></button> <div class="shell"><header class="topbar"><button class="nav-toggle" type="button">Browse topics</button> <div class="brand"><strong>System Design Copilot</strong> <span>0 / 39 lessons complete</span></div></header> <div class="layout"><aside class="sidebar"><section class="sidebar-header panel sidebar-card"><div><p class="eyebrow">System design prep</p> <h2>System Design Copilot</h2></div> <p class="muted">A complete system design interview prep curriculum with topic guides, diagrams, trade-offs, and case studies.</p> <a class="action-link primary" href="../../../../">Open curriculum home</a></section> <section class="panel sidebar-card sidebar-search"><label><span class="eyebrow">Search lessons</span> <input value="" type="search" placeholder="Search modules and topics"/></label></section> <section class="panel sidebar-card sidebar-stats"><article class="stat"><span class="eyebrow">Modules</span> <strong>8</strong></article> <article class="stat"><span class="eyebrow">Progress</span> <strong>0/39</strong></article></section> <!--[0--><!--[--><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations"><strong>Foundations and estimation</strong> <small>Build the habit of turning vague prompts into concrete requirements, scale assumptions, and explicit trade-offs.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/problem-framing"><strong>Problem framing and requirements</strong> <small>Start every design with the user journey, hard constraints, and the two or three metrics that will define success.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/capacity-estimation"><strong>Back-of-the-envelope estimation</strong> <small>Use quick arithmetic to size read/write traffic, storage growth, cache footprint, and inter-service bandwidth before deep diving.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/performance-vs-scalability"><strong>Performance vs. scalability</strong> <small>Performance describes how fast one request path is now; scalability describes how gracefully the system behaves as load, data, or team size grows.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/latency-throughput-slos"><strong>Latency, throughput, and SLOs</strong> <small>Reason about how much work the system can do, how long each request takes, and which percentile targets users actually feel.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/foundations/lesson/availability-consistency-cap"><strong>Availability, consistency, and CAP trade-offs</strong> <small>Designs under partition must choose whether to prioritize fresh coordinated answers or continued service with potentially stale data.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing"><strong>Networking, edge, and request routing</strong> <small>Learn how requests find your system, how traffic is distributed, and where you terminate policy, caching, and security controls.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/dns"><strong>DNS fundamentals</strong> <small>DNS maps names to endpoints and lets you steer traffic geographically, by health, or by weighted rollout without changing clients.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/cdn"><strong>Content delivery networks</strong> <small>A CDN moves cacheable content closer to users and can absorb large amounts of read traffic before requests ever reach origin infrastructure.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/load-balancing"><strong>Load balancing</strong> <small>Load balancers distribute requests across healthy backends and are the main control point for availability, failover, and safe scaling at the service edge.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/reverse-proxies-and-gateways"><strong>Reverse proxies, gateways, and edge policy</strong> <small>Reverse proxies shape inbound traffic by terminating TLS, applying caching and compression, enforcing auth, and routing to internal services.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/edge-and-routing/lesson/rate-limiting-and-edge-protection"><strong>Rate limiting and edge protection</strong> <small>Protect critical services from abusive clients, noisy neighbors, and self-inflicted overload before the core system becomes unstable.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture"><strong>Application architecture and APIs</strong> <small>Choose service boundaries, communication styles, and coordination patterns that fit both the workload and the team operating the system.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/application-layer"><strong>Application layer responsibilities</strong> <small>The application layer turns requests into business actions, coordinates data access, and owns the product semantics that infrastructure alone cannot express.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/monolith-vs-microservices"><strong>Monoliths vs. microservices</strong> <small>Choose decomposition based on coordination cost, deployment independence, and team boundaries rather than trend pressure.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/service-discovery"><strong>Service discovery and coordination</strong> <small>Distributed services need a way to locate healthy instances, coordinate leaders, and react to topology changes without manual reconfiguration.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/api-design"><strong>API design: REST, RPC, and contracts</strong> <small>Pick communication styles that match workflow complexity, evolution needs, and performance sensitivity.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/application-architecture/lesson/realtime-delivery"><strong>Real-time delivery: WebSockets, SSE, and long polling</strong> <small>When users expect live updates, choose a delivery model that matches fan-out shape, connection count, and the direction of data flow.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage"><strong>Data storage and indexing</strong> <small>Match storage engines and data models to access patterns, write volume, consistency needs, and query flexibility.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/relational-data-modeling"><strong>Relational data modeling and indexing</strong> <small>Relational databases remain the default for strongly constrained data, multi-row invariants, and flexible querying with mature operational tooling.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/replication-and-failover"><strong>Replication and failover</strong> <small>Replicas improve read scale, durability, and recovery options, but they introduce lag, failover complexity, and write ownership decisions.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/partitioning-and-sharding"><strong>Partitioning, federation, and sharding</strong> <small>Break data into smaller pieces when a single machine or logical schema becomes the bottleneck for size, throughput, or ownership.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/nosql-landscape"><strong>The NoSQL landscape</strong> <small>NoSQL systems trade some relational flexibility for scale, availability patterns, schema freedom, or specialized query models.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/data-storage/lesson/storage-selection"><strong>Choosing the right storage mix</strong> <small>Most serious systems use more than one storage technology. The skill is choosing a small set whose strengths align with the workload and team.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience"><strong>Caching, asynchrony, and resilience</strong> <small>Reduce latency, smooth bursts, and survive failures by placing the right work in caches, queues, and resilient control loops.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/caching-layers"><strong>Caching layers and cache placement</strong> <small>Caching can remove repeated work from the critical path, but only if you choose the right layer and understand freshness requirements.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/cache-invalidation"><strong>Cache invalidation and update patterns</strong> <small>Pick an update pattern that matches read/write mix, freshness requirements, and operational simplicity.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/queues-and-streams"><strong>Queues, streams, and background work</strong> <small>Move non-interactive or bursty work off the request path so user-facing latency stays bounded and the system can absorb spikes gracefully.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/idempotency-retries-backpressure"><strong>Idempotency, retries, and back pressure</strong> <small>Make distributed workflows safe under duplicate delivery, partial failure, and overload instead of assuming every call succeeds exactly once.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/performance-and-resilience/lesson/observability"><strong>Observability and operational feedback loops</strong> <small>Metrics, logs, traces, and alerting turn architecture choices into something operators can actually trust and improve.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations"><strong>Security, multi-region, and operations</strong> <small>Design systems that are safe to expose, recoverable during disasters, and maintainable by real teams over time.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 4 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/security-basics"><strong>Security foundations for system design</strong> <small>Security choices should appear throughout the design, not as a last-minute box labeled auth.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/multi-region-disaster-recovery"><strong>Multi-region design and disaster recovery</strong> <small>Use multiple regions when the business case justifies lower outage risk, lower latency, or data residency needs, while accepting the added coordination cost.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/fault-tolerance-and-graceful-degradation"><strong>Fault tolerance and graceful degradation</strong> <small>Healthy systems keep the core user journey alive when dependencies fail by shedding optional work and falling back to simpler behavior.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/deployment-capacity-cost"><strong>Deployments, capacity, and cost awareness</strong> <small>Production systems need safe release mechanics, realistic capacity headroom, and an explicit understanding of what the architecture costs to run.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns"><strong>Common product design patterns</strong> <small>Practice recurring architectures that appear across many interview prompts and real-world products.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/feed-timeline"><strong>Feeds and timelines</strong> <small>Feeds combine ranking, fan-out, caching, and read-time assembly decisions under heavy skewed traffic.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/file-storage-cdn"><strong>File upload, processing, and distribution</strong> <small>Media-heavy products require a pipeline for uploads, validation, durable storage, transformation, and fast global delivery.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/search-autocomplete"><strong>Search and autocomplete</strong> <small>Search systems combine ingestion, indexing, ranking, caching, and query-time latency controls.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/chat-notifications"><strong>Chat, presence, and notifications</strong> <small>Messaging products blend low-latency delivery, persistent history, fan-out, device state, and notification fallbacks.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/product-patterns/lesson/payments-ledger"><strong>Payments and ledger-style systems</strong> <small>Money movement demands idempotency, auditability, reconciliation, and a conservative approach to asynchronous side effects.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><section class="nav-module"><div><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies"><strong>Case studies and interview drills</strong> <small>Apply the concepts to end-to-end systems that commonly appear in interviews and architecture reviews.</small></a></div> <span class="pill">0 / 5 complete</span> <div class="nav-links"><!--[--><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/url-shortener"><strong>Case study: URL shortener</strong> <small>Design a service that creates short codes, resolves them quickly, tracks analytics, and avoids hot-key failures.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/web-crawler"><strong>Case study: distributed web crawler</strong> <small>Crawlers combine frontier management, politeness, deduplication, storage, and ranking across many workers.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/social-graph"><strong>Case study: social graph service</strong> <small>A social graph stores user relationships, supports high-volume fan-out queries, and powers many downstream ranking and recommendation systems.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/query-cache"><strong>Case study: query-result cache</strong> <small>Design a cache that stores expensive query results while handling invalidation, skew, and freshness guarantees.</small></a><a class="nav-link " href="../../../../module/case-studies/lesson/scaling-playbook"><strong>Case study: scaling playbook</strong> <small>Practice describing how a simple single-region web application evolves through caching, queueing, partitioning, and global distribution over multiple growth stages.</small></a><!--]--></div></section><!--]--><!--]--></aside> <main class="page"><!--[--><!--[--><section class="panel hero-card"><div class="breadcrumb"><a href="../../../../">Curriculum</a> <span>→</span> <a href="../../../../module/security-and-operations">Security, multi-region, and operations</a> <span>→</span> <span>Deployments, capacity, and cost awareness</span></div> <p class="eyebrow">Lesson 4 of 4</p> <h1>Deployments, capacity, and cost awareness</h1> <p class="hero-subtitle">Production systems need safe release mechanics, realistic capacity headroom, and an explicit understanding of what the architecture costs to run.</p> <div class="action-row"><span class="pill">25-35 min</span> <span class="pill">Security, multi-region, and operations</span> <button class="lesson-toggle" type="button">Mark complete</button></div></section> <section class="section-grid"><div class="content-grid"><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Why it matters</p> <h3>Interview framing</h3> <p>A design is incomplete if it only works in steady state and ignores change management or economics.</p></article> <!--[--><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Release safely</h3> <p>Rolling deploys, canaries, blue-green releases, and feature flags reduce the blast radius of changes.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Drain connections before terminating nodes</li><li>Use progressive exposure for risky changes</li><li>Keep schema migrations backward compatible across mixed-version deploys</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Plan headroom and autoscaling</h3> <p>Capacity should account for growth, burst, maintenance events, and failover scenarios, not only average load.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Scale on saturation signals that precede user pain</li><li>Preserve buffer for regional failover or deploy overlap</li><li>Model the cost of always-on capacity versus queueing and batch work</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><article class="content-card"><p class="eyebrow">Study section</p> <h3>Cost is part of the trade-off</h3> <p>Egress, replication, storage classes, idle capacity, and operational labor all matter. The cheapest architecture on paper may be the most expensive to operate.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Use cost-aware storage tiers</li><li>Cache and CDN decisions often shift both latency and egress cost</li><li>Overly fragmented architectures increase people cost</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><!--]--></div> <div class="content-grid"><!--[-1--><!--]--> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Checklist</p> <h3>Things to say clearly</h3> <ul class="checklist"><!--[--><li>Mention a release strategy and rollback plan.</li><li>Reserve capacity for bursts and failover.</li><li>Discuss cost drivers such as egress, replicas, and idle headroom.</li><li>Prefer simple architectures when they meet the requirements.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Common pitfalls</p> <h3>What to avoid</h3> <ul class="pitfalls"><!--[--><li>Ignoring schema compatibility during rolling deploys.</li><li>Sizing only for averages.</li><li>Pretending cost is someone else’s problem.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interview prompts</p> <h3>Practice aloud</h3> <ul class="prompts"><!--[--><li>How would you deploy a risky ranking change safely?</li><li>Why do failover scenarios affect capacity planning?</li><li>What are the biggest hidden costs in a globally distributed system?</li><!--]--></ul></article></div></section> <section class="panel hero-card"><div class="action-row" style="justify-content: space-between; align-items: end;"><div><p class="eyebrow">Next steps</p> <h2>Keep moving through the module</h2></div></div> <div class="action-row"><!--[0--><a class="action-link" href="../../../../module/security-and-operations/lesson/fault-tolerance-and-graceful-degradation">← Fault tolerance and graceful degradation</a><!--]--> <!--[-1--><a class="action-link primary" href="../../../../">Back to curriculum</a><!--]--></div></section><!--]--><!--]--></main></div></div><!--]--><!--]--> <!--[-1--><!--]--><!--]-->
