tional ambiguity.</p> <!--[0--><ul><!--[--><li>Protect write endpoints from replay and forgery</li><li>Validate and sanitize user input by context</li><li>Use least privilege for services and operators</li><!--]--></ul><!--]--></article><!--]--></div> <div class="content-grid"><!--[-1--><!--]--> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Checklist</p> <h3>Things to say clearly</h3> <ul class="checklist"><!--[--><li>Separate authn from authz.</li><li>Encrypt transport and sensitive data at rest.</li><li>Apply least privilege to services and operators.</li><li>Mention abuse prevention and auditability.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Common pitfalls</p> <h3>What to avoid</h3> <ul class="pitfalls"><!--[--><li>Treating security as one edge component with no data-flow impact.</li><li>Granting broad internal trust without service identity.</li><li>Ignoring operational controls such as key rotation or audit logs.</li><!--]--></ul></article> <article class="list-card"><p class="eyebrow">Interview prompts</p> <h3>Practice aloud</h3> <ul class="prompts"><!--[--><li>What security controls are mandatory for a payments system?</li><li>How would you design authz for a multi-tenant admin dashboard?</li><li>Why is least privilege important between internal services?</li><!--]--></ul></article></div></section> <section class="panel hero-card practice-workspace"><div class="action-row" style="justify-content: space-between; align-items: end;"><div><p class="eyebrow">Interactive practice lab</p> <h2>Write, save, and move through the mock interview</h2> <p class="practice-copy">Answers stay in your browser so you can come back later without needing automated grading.</p></div> <div class="practice-status-group"><span class="pill">0/3 prompts saved</span> <span class="pill">Prompt 1 of 3</span></div></div> <div class="practice-layout"><article class="list-card practice-outline"><p class="eyebrow">Prompt flow</p> <h3>What you will practice</h3